Cycles will come and go but, sound businesses will get built and funded regardless! 

So, to all of us here in india: stay hungry, stay foolish and keep building! 🇮🇳

latestPosts.caption:
⚡Goodbye @dr.vaidyas ⚡
 
Trisha Rajani & I had the opportunity to start @dr.vaidyas 4 years ago with just 6 people. This week - our baby got acquired. I remember celebrating every win and every new customer - dreaming that our office would be full one day. Fast forward to today - many mistakes and some big wins later, we are a family of 70+ products, 140+ team members and 1 million + customers.
 
We grew up with this company. We came here as young, first time entrepreneurs and this journey taught us passion, hard work and the indomitable spirit to keep fighting. We got engaged and married but, the majority of our time was spent in this office thinking of new products, growth and milestones.
 
As we bid adieu soon, it's important to say thank you.
 
To all of you - our vendors, partners, customers & critics. You made this journey what it was & pushed us to get better!

To our team - continue to be the most hard working, passionate and agile bunch as it customary at DRV.
 
To my Dada - our force, I hope you’re proud of where we’ve come.
 
For Trisha and I, we’ve been the lucky to have this journey and feel even luckier to leave our baby in strong hands of our investors for its next chapter of growth. 

The first test of our life’s 5 match series is over, but for now – time for a holiday…
#d2c #exit #drvaidyas #newageayurveda #proudlyindian

India won’t be held back by money, tech or talent.
It’ll be held back by mindset.

We’ve glamorised jugaad for too long.
Adjusted. Ignored. Moved on.

But if we want to lead globally,
we have to stop calling selfishness “smart”
and start calling it what it is —
a lack of basic civil sense.

Charity starts at home.
So does change.

Happy Father’s Day to my hero, my guru, my mentor @vaidyabiren 

Every year I reflect on what my dad has taught me. It’s all stuff that is dated. But, today it’s more recent and something, I haven’t shared. 

A few months ago, my dad had a serious health setback. It hit all of us hard.
Honestly, I didn’t fully get the gravity at the time.

And then when I did. For the first time ever, I felt responsible for him. And I was scared.

Seeing him go from being the busiest person in the world - to being at home. In and out of hospitals for two months was v tough.

But, this below me away. 
His spirit never changed.
From running his company to growing plants at home. He was still happy. 
He was still laughing before surgery.
Still cracking jokes after.
Still saying things like:
“Don’t take life too seriously — it’s a video game.”

He’s 70% back now. And I know he’ll be 100% soon.

I’ve always learned from him.

But in these months — I learned even more.
How to be positive when life throws a massive curveball. How to smile through pain. And, how to stay grounded through it all.

If I can be half the father he’s been to me…
Aisha’s in good hands.

Thanks dad. For everything :)

India isn’t just the king of mangoes it’s sitting on a billion-dollar export opportunity.

We grow nearly half the world’s mangoes, and last year alone, exports hit ₹420 crore with Saudi Arabia leading the charge.

This isn’t just about fruit. 

It’s about rural jobs, farmer income, and Indian soft power on global tables.

From Ratnagiri to Riyadh mangoes might just be our next global flex.

India’s coffee market is worth $5 billion — and it’s just getting started.
But most brands are still stuck in plain vanilla offerings.

This founder from Jaipur is building a flavoured coffee company — with bold SKUs like chocolate-orange, cranberry, and mint.
Bootstrapped, and still managed ₹1.7 Cr in revenue.
Built a solid B2B base with hotels and cafes.
And now wants to scale through retail and digital.

The numbers are decent.
The clarity is strong.
And the market is wide open for disruption.

That’s why I’m taking a second meeting — to go deeper into the product, brand potential, and how big this can really get.

We live in a country where camels can’t survive the heat.
But our frontline workers are out delivering in it — every single day.

Nimbu paani and chhaas aren’t enough anymore.
India needs a new-age hydration format — functional, clean, affordable, and built for the masses.

Glucon-D × Lahori Jeera for 2025.
A ₹5 sachet that scales like chai.

Can electrolytes become India’s next big FMCG category?

latestPosts.caption:
Comet Shoes, founded by Nishant and Utkarsh, has quietly cracked the code of modern brand-building. 

Instead of chasing hype, they tapped into the power of UGC and built tight-knit communities around everyday style.

Their secret? Designing sneakers that feel premium but are priced for daily wear and creating a brand that talks like the people. 

No influencers, no gimmicks  just real people repping real shoes. They didn’t chase the 1%. 

They built for the rest of us. And it worked.
